\begin_layout Subsection
Legendre method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To build a synthetic abundancies sample with the Legendre method just type
 the command:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout LyX-Code
[abundanciesSample] = getAbundanciesSampleLegendre();
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
that will create a sample of abundancies images with the default parameters
 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:abundSampleLegendreDef"

\end_inset

).
 The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

abundanceSample
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will be a matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $256\times256\times5$
\end_inset

 elements, being the first and second the spatial dimensions and the last
 the number of abundancies images.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The parameters used by the Legendre method are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ne: number of abundancies images in the sample (default: 5).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
npoints: spatial dimensions of the abundancies images, the images are squared
 so only one parameter is needed (default: 256).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
minOrder,maxOrder: minimum and maximum orders of the Legendre polynomies
 (defaults: 1,10).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
maxCoef: weighting coeficient to bias the Legendre polynomies (default:
 100).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An use example could be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
[abundanciesSample] = 
\end_layout

\begin_layout LyX-Code
getAbundanciesSampleLegendre(3,64,1,5,50);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
that will create a sample of 3 abundancies images with 64 pixels-height
 and width, and with minOrder, maxOrder and maxCoef equals to 1, 10 and
 50 respectively (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:abundSampleLegendreParams"

\end_inset

).
 In this case the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

abundanceSample
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 will be a matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $64\times64\times3$
\end_inset

 elements, being the first and second the spatial dimensions and the last
 the number of abundancies images.
\end_layout

